%md
### Hough Lines Detection and Draw Function

Create a for loop calling it for line in lines, lines is the number of lines, x1,y1,x2,y2 are the different starting and ending points that have been detected within the image. Every iteration, go and grab x1,y1,x2,y2 within my line and take my blank **line_image** and draw lines with all these starting and ending points in there with a specified line color using **cv2.line()**. Then the new image layer with lanes detected within the region of interest will be placed on top of the original colored image to illustrate lane detection using **cv2.addWeighted()**.

msg.data:
Hough Lines Detection and Draw Function

Create a for loop calling it for line in lines, lines is the number of lines, x1,y1,x2,y2 are the different starting and ending points that have been detected within the image. Every iteration, go and grab x1,y1,x2,y2 within my line and take my blank line_image and draw lines with all these starting and ending points in there with a specified line color using cv2.line(). Then the new image layer with lanes detected within the region of interest will be placed on top of the original colored image to illustrate lane detection using cv2.addWeighted().

paragraphs.text:
%python
# Distance resolution in pixels
rho = 2
# Angular Resolution in Radians
theta = np.pi/180
# Minimum Number of Votes
threshold = 40
# Minimum Number of pixels makeing up a line
min_line_len = 100
# Maximum gap in pixels between connectable line segments
max_line_gap = 50
lines = cv2.HoughLinesP(masked_image, rho, theta, threshold, np.array([]), minLineLength=min_line_len, maxLineGap=max_line_gap )

# Create an empty black image
line_image = np.zeros((masked_image.shape[0], masked_image.shape[1], 3), dtype=np.uint8)

for line in lines:
    for x1, y1, x2, y2 in line:
        cv2.line(line_image, (x1,y1), (x2,y2), [0,255,0], 20)
        
lines
